        "execSummary":  "CrowdStrike\u0027s identification of five new prompt injection classes is a concrete signal that the AI security threat surface is expanding faster than most enterprise security programs have accounted for in their AI governance frameworks. For senior leaders deploying AI agents that process external content ΓÇö emails, documents, web data, customer inputs ΓÇö each of these attack vectors represents a live risk today, not a theoretical future concern. The practical implication is that standard penetration testing methodologies do not cover AI-specific attack surfaces; dedicated AI red-teaming and adversarial input testing need to be added to security review cycles for any AI deployment. Organizations that have not yet mapped their AI systems\u0027 exposure to untrusted input channels should treat this as an urgent audit item before the next model expansion.",
        "vendorLean":  "CrowdStrike ΓÇö research is published by CrowdStrike, positioning their threat intelligence and detection capabilities.",
        "imageUrl":  "https://www.infoworld.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/4195672-0-46209900-1783694089-shutterstock_2518359167.jpg"
